Approach: Binary Search on the Partition
Intuition
Instead of actually merging the two sorted arrays, we imagine that they have already been merged into one sorted array.

Our goal is to find the correct partition such that:

The left half contains exactly half of the total elements (one extra element if the total length is odd).
Every element on the left is less than or equal to every element on the right.
If we can find such a partition, then:

For an odd total length, the median is simply the largest element on the left.
For an even total length, the median is the average of the largest element on the left and the smallest element on the right.
Key Observation
Suppose we choose a partition in nums1.

Then the partition in nums2 is automatically determined because the total number of elements on the left side is fixed.

partition2 = leftHalf - partition1
where

leftHalf = (n1 + n2 + 1) // 2
This reduces the problem to searching for only one partition.

Why Binary Search?
We binary search only on the smaller array.

For every partition:

l1 = largest element on the left side of nums1
r1 = smallest element on the right side of nums1
l2 = largest element on the left side of nums2
r2 = smallest element on the right side of nums2
The partition is valid if:

l1 <= r2
and
l2 <= r1
If:

l1 > r2
then we have taken too many elements from nums1, so we move the partition to the left.

If:

l2 > r1
then we have taken too few elements from nums1, so we move the partition to the right.

Since each step halves the search space, binary search efficiently finds the correct partition.

Boundary Handling
The partition can lie before the first element or after the last element of an array.

To handle these edge cases uniformly:

If there is no element on the left, we treat it as -∞.
If there is no element on the right, we treat it as +∞.
This avoids writing separate logic for boundary cases while keeping the partition conditions unchanged.

Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity: O(log(min(n, m)))

Binary search is performed only on the smaller array.
Space Complexity: O(1)

Only a few variables are used.
Code
class Solution:
    def findMedianSortedArrays(self, nums1: List[int], nums2: List[int]) -> float:
        n1 = len(nums1)
        n2 = len(nums2)
        if n1 >n2:
            return self.findMedianSortedArrays(nums2,nums1)
        low = 0 
        high = n1
        left_half = (n1+n2+1)//2
        n = n1+n2

        while low <= high:
            partition1 = (low+high)//2
            partition2 = left_half - partition1

            if partition1 == 0:
                l1 = float('-inf')
            else:
                l1 = nums1[partition1-1]
            
            if partition1 == n1:
                r1 = float('inf')
            else:
                r1 = nums1[partition1]
            
            if partition2 == 0:
                l2 = float('-inf')
            else:
                l2 = nums2[partition2-1]
            
            if partition2 == n2:
                r2 = float('inf')
            else:
                r2 = nums2[partition2]
            
            if l1 <= r2 and l2 <= r1:
                if n % 2 == 1:
                    return max(l1,l2)
                else:
                    return (max(l1,l2) + min(r1,r2))/2
            
            elif l1 > r2:
                high = partition1 - 1
            else:
                low = partition1 + 1
